******

Gerone is the tired uncle who showed me out of his summer home. He’s too responsible to let an uprooted American drink and freak out in Albania. He tries to give me a pep talk about being careful out on the American road “with these special corporations that you seem so interested in,” and tells me I had better call him when I get home.

He cares about me more than I ever cared about him in my short time with him this week.

Yet he’s also one in a long line of Albanians I have met, stressed out about something their forefathers caused. Soccer is caused by Distize, a huge electrical plant that Jeppo and Carlos talked about, so full of PC games that only electronic light fights with neon colors are allowed inside.

Waterfalls are caused by the hydroelectric power plants that Meliha is trying to leave Kayham for. Adam makes bank because of Durrës’ luxurious villas for Albanian politicians. City hall was built by a grandfather or a great-grandfather paying off a strongman long ago with a promise to only let him be mayor.

The homeland: forever the source of problems from which Albanians charge so hard for freedom.

Carlos is the new generation in a family where “running away” was inevitable after an experience at Guendalina Stadium last week. Staying is inevitable
